review_blob: Bottle from Booths Supermarket, Windermere.  Great tasking cumbrian beer.  Low carbonation gives it a nice smooth taste.  Good body no bitterness and quite sweet tasting.  Best served slightly chilled.  Good.

Cask, The Crescent Hotel, Scarborough.  Reasonably well kept for a hotel bar although cold at first.  Nice tasting beer full bodied given its 3.7% gravity.  Sweet aftertaste.  Excellent session beer.  Nice.
Cask Marble Arch known as Pint - Loverly light session beer.  We didnt get around to trying any of their other beers because this was was so good.

Bottle from Pochers off licence, Lincoln.  Its not often that I could pour a beer down the sink, but I nearly did this one.  It was gassy and the head filled half my pint glass once poured.  Once it settled it was a clear golden colour, but smelt terrible and tasted very acidy.  I struggled to get it down Im afriad.  I bought two bottles but wont be having the second.

Cask, The Drunken Duck Inn, Barngates near Ambleside.  Was looking forward to trying this as the previous time I went to The Duck it wasnt on.  Slightly disappointed with it to be honest.  Nice colour, but a bit cool and hazy and the taste was quite blande and bitter.  Worth a try, but not one of their best but perhaps this was a one off.  Some staff cannot pour a decent pint here, which is suprising given that the brewery is on site.

Cask at The Victoria, Lincoln.  Used to be known as Union Gold, this is a lovely light gold pale ale with a good session strength.  Quite perfumy on the nose and sometimes slightly bitter, but very quaffable all the same.  Its a regular beer in The Victoria, so always have one of these before trying one of the guest beers.  To the bar....
Cask @ The Victoria, Lincoln.  Good for a batemans beer.  Golden to pale, thick, full bodied and very tasty.  Butter and caramel present.  Very nice indeed.
Cask @ Lichfield Beer Festival and The Victoria, Lincoln.  Golden to dark beer very tasty.  Quite sweet.  One of my favourite beers.

Bottle (not bottle conditioned) from Watermill Ings.  At 2.70 ish a bottle direct from the brewery this is expensive.  I wanted to try it though and it didnt disappoint.  Its 5% strength gives it good body.  A thick, pale / golden ale with sweet aromas and a clean crisp finish.  Very nice, if expensive for a bottled beer brewed on site - exploiting the tourists Im afraid.

Bottle (not bottle conditioned) from Watermill Ings, plus cask also tried at the Watermill.  A nice pale ale with a sweet aroma.  Lacks body but still a good tasting low gravity beer.  Bottle uses low carbonation so it gets away with not being bottle conditioned.  Worth a try.

Bottle conditioned from Morrisons.  Pale golden beer, slightly bitter, but smooth and pleasant tasting.  Carbonated, but this is generated by the natural bottled conditioned element.  Overall a decent pale ale for drinking at home.

Bottle conditioned from Doddington Farm Shop near Lincoln, Lincs.  Golden to dark beer poored clear and flat, almost like it was direct from the cask.  A good bottle conditioned beer.  Slight earthy taste, but still good.

Cask at the Drunken Duck Inn, Barngates.  First few pints I tried were clear and tasty, however, on a recent visit it poored with a slight haze and had a very bitter finish and was slightly cool.  Still a nice pale ale given that its only 3.6%.  Hit and miss high turnover staff at the Drunken Duck some of which cannot poor a decent pint, which affects the quality of the beer.

Bottle from Booths Supermarket.  A tasty beer considering it is not bottle conditioned.  First bottles were hazy, but more recent ones are polished and very clear.  A good bodied bottled beer from this excellent small brewery linked to the Drunken Duck near Ambleside.

Bottle conditioned, direct from the brewery.  Poored quite hazy and flat, almost like it was direct from the cask.  Smokey in taste at first, but grows on you.  If they could polish the apperance this beer is worth trying.
